16:["$","p",null,{"children":["The harder question is scale. Boston Dynamics has yet to disclose pricing, but industry players note that humanoid robots at this capability level typically run ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"six figures per unit"}],"—before custom integration. Then there’s reliability: Atlas’ hydraulic system, while advanced, requires ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.ieee.org/content/dam/ieee/org/ras/PDFs/2023/Atlas_Hydraulics_Whitepaper.pdf","children":"rigorous maintenance"}]," to avoid leaks or actuator fatigue under industrial loads. And safety certification? Still pending for most jurisdictions, meaning wide deployment is years away, not months."]}]
17:["$","p",null,{"children":["For now, Atlas remains what it’s always been: a spectacular ",["$","em",null,{"children":"demo"}]," searching for a problem it can solve at scale. The Hyundai partnership is progress, but it’s also a reminder that the gap between a viral video and a viable product is measured in ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"uptime, not press releases"}],"."]}]
18:["$","p",null,{"children":"Can Atlas survive a year on the factory floor without a dedicated engineering team on standby? That’s the question the demo reels won’t answer—and the one that determines whether this is a product or just another expensive science project."}]
